1
00:00:01,550 --> 00:00:29,615
Namo tassa bhagavato harhato sambha sambuddhasa Namo tassa bhagavato harhato sambha sambuddhasa Namo tassa bhagavato harhato sambha sambuddhasa

2
00:00:30,440 --> 00:00:35,226
Homage to the Buddha, the blessed, noble and fully self-enlightened one.

3
00:00:40,835 --> 00:00:50,389
This evening I'd just like to spend the usual time, 10-15 minutes on just the things that have come up during the day and certain questions.

4
00:00:54,895 --> 00:00:59,502
The first one is this business of when I talk about the process of purification.

5
00:00:59,835 --> 00:01:08,771
So that's what I mean partly by emotional purification and partly by mental purification.

6
00:01:09,412 --> 00:01:22,332
So the purity of the heart is the transformation of all that negative side of our experience, you know, depression, anxiety, you name it, you know, the whole gamut of human misery.

7
00:01:22,313 --> 00:01:33,115
and to transform it into its opposites.

8
00:01:34,158 --> 00:01:38,888
So where there's depression, there's joy, where there's boredom, there's interest, and so on.

9
00:01:39,965 --> 00:01:40,725
That's the process.

10
00:01:40,805 --> 00:01:44,629
It's going from darkness to light, darkness to light.

11
00:01:45,390 --> 00:01:50,075
And the emotional purification is done by bearing it.

12
00:01:50,394 --> 00:02:05,870
First of all, by bearing the product of what we've created and by making sure we don't unwittingly develop it through fantasy and through our actions, through speech and body.

13
00:02:07,031 --> 00:02:08,052
So that's all that means.

14
00:02:08,373 --> 00:02:13,640
In other words, it associates very closely to what we would normally mean by psychotherapy.

15
00:02:14,882 --> 00:02:22,793
The added thing, of course, is the spiritual dimension goes down to the core root as to why we're suffering.

16
00:02:22,812 --> 00:02:24,855
And that's where it becomes a spiritual practice.

17
00:02:25,175 --> 00:02:28,700
So we're not really concerned as such with emotions.

18
00:02:28,820 --> 00:02:31,204
We're not concerned as such with wandering thoughts.

19
00:02:31,905 --> 00:02:33,967
We're trying to get underneath it, you see.

20
00:02:35,820 --> 00:02:46,700
Just while I'm on emotions, I don't know, I've mentioned it to one or two groups, but there's the divide between the feminine and the masculine.

21
00:02:46,721 --> 00:02:48,585
Have I mentioned that with emotions?

22
00:02:49,126 --> 00:02:49,866
Have I mentioned that?

23
00:02:50,147 --> 00:02:50,288
No.

24
00:02:50,829 --> 00:02:55,837
Well, the feminine person, you note I don't say female,

25
00:02:55,818 --> 00:03:01,032
A feminine person tends to be much closer to their emotions.

26
00:03:01,614 --> 00:03:04,662
They're the sort of person who says, I feel, I feel.

27
00:03:05,324 --> 00:03:11,801
And on the other end, of course, the masculine tends to be in the head, and they normally start sentences with, I think.

28
00:03:11,782 --> 00:03:37,265
So, when a person is very close to their emotions, feeling emotions, and they come to meditation, because they know their emotions, because they've always identified with them, because they've always had this relationship of possessing them, it's very difficult for them to create that distance that I keep talking about, to look at it, because the habit is to go into it and feel, experience those emotions.

29
00:03:37,246 --> 00:03:49,973
so for those sorts of people if you go underneath the idea of an emotion if you go to the body and feel it as sensation

30
00:03:51,050 --> 00:04:14,627
heat nausea heaviness instead of seeing it as an emotion to see it just as physical feelings they regain their objectivity and it's not a suppressive measure it's just a different view of what it is because in the Buddha's understanding it's all feeling it's all feeling it all comes under one word Vedana physical and mental feelings

31
00:04:15,502 --> 00:04:25,855
And just by being there with those feelings and just feeling them at the level of sensation, you know, physical sensation, we're still allowing that energy to dissipate.

32
00:04:26,557 --> 00:04:27,942
And that's the curing.

33
00:04:28,781 --> 00:04:30,223
That's the healing of that process.

34
00:04:31,225 --> 00:04:42,584
On the masculine side, it depends how, you know, this is a big generalization, but often if people have lived in their heads, they've thought their emotions.

35
00:04:42,603 --> 00:04:44,007
They haven't actually felt their emotions.

36
00:04:44,026 --> 00:04:48,312
So when they come to meditation and feel their emotions, it's a big shock.

37
00:04:48,333 --> 00:04:53,641
And the shock means that they maintain that distance because they've never felt this stuff before.

38
00:04:54,449 --> 00:04:59,564
So for them, they can remain more easily with emotions as emotions.

39
00:04:59,697 --> 00:05:27,476
so just yourself, just put yourself on that line somewhere there are some emotions which we allow ourselves to feel and we justify them anger for instance, things like that and there are other emotions that we don't we don't justify jealousy and stuff like that we don't like to look at that guilt, remorse, sometimes that's all hidden away so even though I've talked very generally but actually everyone has a bit of masculine and feminine in them obviously

40
00:05:34,173 --> 00:05:38,139
Remember that we're not trying to destroy the reasoning mind.

41
00:05:38,880 --> 00:05:41,004
We're not trying to destroy thought.

42
00:05:41,725 --> 00:05:43,247
We're trying to be able to stop it.

43
00:05:44,470 --> 00:05:49,579
The enlightened person, if they don't want to think, they don't think, the thoughts don't arise.

44
00:05:49,639 --> 00:05:54,026
I remember Krishnamurti saying that when he went for a walk in a forest, the thought never arose.

45
00:05:54,646 --> 00:05:56,269
When he went for a walk, the thought never arose.

46
00:05:57,091 --> 00:06:00,096
He was just there with walking through the forest.

47
00:06:01,627 --> 00:06:03,870
It's not a destruction of thought.

48
00:06:03,970 --> 00:06:11,577
Again, remember that thought is always driven by some mental state, by some emotion, by some motivation.

49
00:06:13,100 --> 00:06:14,600
I'm talking about just ordinary thinking.

50
00:06:16,043 --> 00:06:30,117
So now, as we purify the mind, and this intelligence, this satipanya, this knowing, understands something, it cannot come to know what it knows until it tells itself through thought.

51
00:06:30,973 --> 00:06:33,437
That's the paradox.

52
00:06:33,459 --> 00:06:43,877
So when the Buddha's enlightened, it's not as though he came out and just sort of laid out a big book saying four noble truths, eightfold path, weird benedictionation, boom, boom, off I go.

53
00:06:44,658 --> 00:06:46,141
It wasn't like that at all.

54
00:06:46,221 --> 00:06:52,492
He came out, he knew that he'd experienced something, and he went along and he began to teach, and he taught...

55
00:06:52,911 --> 00:07:14,110
individuals and the teaching came out so if you look at the early parts of the scriptures they're very spontaneous they're not particularly rigidified or or made into lists or anything of that nature and then in the middle section you suddenly start getting appearing these lists and of course they're there for memory and suddenly these lists appear

56
00:07:15,810 --> 00:07:21,439
And of course the whole teaching then becomes much more of a logical framework.

57
00:07:21,459 --> 00:07:25,725
Just for one very simple thing, he talks about the 37 factors of enlightenment.

58
00:07:27,708 --> 00:07:33,175
We talked about the 7 factors of enlightenment, that's one thing, but the whole teaching is the 37 factors of enlightenment.

59
00:07:33,196 --> 00:07:37,762
The whole of the Buddhist teaching is enclosed in the 37 factors of enlightenment.

60
00:07:38,262 --> 00:07:41,767
Now, there were 37 musical chords at the time.

61
00:07:42,894 --> 00:07:51,673
So it's a number which everybody, shall we say, it's in the back of their minds as an important number, as a mystical number, as something like that.

62
00:07:52,108 --> 00:07:55,754
And it so happens that his teaching comes out to be 37.

63
00:07:55,894 --> 00:08:11,096
He fiddles a bit because the five spiritual faculties, he also says they're five strengths, unshakable strengths when one has actually intuited nibbana.

64
00:08:11,456 --> 00:08:16,024
So there's a bit of a sort of double take to get his 37, which is all right.

65
00:08:19,160 --> 00:08:23,074
Talking about that, when I mention the Enlightenment, these are big words.

66
00:08:23,396 --> 00:08:24,601
If they don't grab you, forget it.

67
00:08:25,504 --> 00:08:29,540
Our work is groundwork, our work is dogwork.

68
00:08:29,706 --> 00:08:31,069
You know, we're at the coalface here.

69
00:08:31,550 --> 00:08:40,061
Enlightenment is just a word pointing to some sort of end game, there's some sort of process where we're moving towards it.

70
00:08:40,761 --> 00:08:43,125
When we say we're moving towards it, we're not creating it.

71
00:08:43,846 --> 00:08:51,376
If you take a train from Newton Abbot to London, it's not as though London is being created by the time you get there.

72
00:08:51,356 --> 00:09:20,200
it's already there so this enlightenment the Mahayana are very good on this we're already enlightened that's not a problem just we don't know it that's the problem and to get to know it they have to go through this whole process of purifying the heart because the impurities in the heart the distortions in the mind are the measure of our delusions so we're coming back on delusions we're coming back on misunderstandings on mistakes we've made

73
00:09:20,904 --> 00:09:24,428
So don't worry about words like enlightenment, nibbana.

74
00:09:26,370 --> 00:09:28,734
Just let them one ear and out the other.

75
00:09:34,821 --> 00:09:37,683
You know, these days we expect things to be very quick.

76
00:09:37,724 --> 00:09:48,515
I mean, if I wake up and I've got an earache, by nine o'clock I'm at the doctor's and he puts something in it, take a tablet and the thing's gone.

77
00:09:49,086 --> 00:09:55,493
The car breaks down, I can phone up a service and it'll be mended within an easy time, half a day or something.

78
00:09:55,513 --> 00:09:58,176
So when we come to this sort of work, we think, well, you know what?

79
00:09:59,177 --> 00:10:00,418
I've been here for a few days now.

80
00:10:00,638 --> 00:10:01,839
I've done this for weeks.

81
00:10:01,879 --> 00:10:02,639
I've done this for years.

82
00:10:04,020 --> 00:10:05,302
And not much seems to have happened.

83
00:10:07,024 --> 00:10:09,046
Then you start getting a bit depressed about it.

84
00:10:10,206 --> 00:10:14,892
But what I would say to you is that when you look back over a period of time,

85
00:10:15,344 --> 00:10:21,131
especially if you look back something like five, six, seven years, you can definitely see a change within yourself.

86
00:10:21,572 --> 00:10:24,076
There is a change, there's a change going on, but it's very subtle.

87
00:10:24,937 --> 00:10:27,181
And why does it take so much time?

88
00:10:27,542 --> 00:10:29,904
It's because of the strength of these conditionings.

89
00:10:30,725 --> 00:10:33,850
I mean, those of you who drink tea, just stop drinking tea.

90
00:10:34,731 --> 00:10:36,014
You know, it's hell.

91
00:10:37,797 --> 00:10:40,120
When I stop drinking tea, you'll know I'm enlightened.

92
00:10:44,234 --> 00:11:11,018
so you know when I'll be talking this a bit more at the end I don't want to touch on it too much so the teachers that you come across we're practically as unenlightened as you all we've done is a bit more training you know we've sort of had maybe some good insights some reading a bit you know and all that sort of stuff spend a bit more time than most people and that's it we're on the same path

93
00:11:16,549 --> 00:11:24,903
When an idea comes up in your head in meditation which seems to you absolutely sublime, like suddenly you think, I'm going to create a charity to help the lepers in India.

94
00:11:26,265 --> 00:11:27,748
You think, that's very, very good.

95
00:11:28,590 --> 00:11:32,115
Now, I'll think about that.

96
00:11:32,937 --> 00:11:33,378
Yeah.

97
00:11:34,720 --> 00:11:34,960
See?

98
00:11:35,600 --> 00:11:36,582
Now that's not meditation.

99
00:11:38,875 --> 00:11:52,754
Even beautiful, wonderful, sublime desires and ideas are, as far as we're concerned, in this retreat, for this period of time, just a mental aberration to be noted and to let go of.

100
00:11:53,054 --> 00:12:00,424
If you really, really are interested in setting something up for lepers in India, write a little note and come back to it at the end of the week.

101
00:12:00,445 --> 00:12:02,327
There is nothing wrong with that lovely idea.

102
00:12:04,850 --> 00:12:06,232
There's lots of lepers in India, aren't there?

103
00:12:09,993 --> 00:12:12,596
Sometimes the body shakes jerks in meditation.

104
00:12:12,998 --> 00:12:17,625
So that's just this energy, you see, you know, caught up in the body.

105
00:12:18,106 --> 00:12:19,950
And it's trying to release itself.

106
00:12:19,970 --> 00:12:24,557
So it could be quite, you know, I remember somebody sort of shaking his head like this, you know.

107
00:12:26,760 --> 00:12:28,565
I kept saying, yes, yes, yes.

108
00:12:28,585 --> 00:12:30,027
And he was...

109
00:12:31,171 --> 00:12:35,320
But sometimes it's a sort of swaying and it feels good.

110
00:12:35,360 --> 00:12:37,485
Of course it feels good because it's letting off this energy.

111
00:12:38,125 --> 00:12:39,288
So what you do is you stop.

112
00:12:40,049 --> 00:12:40,692
You stop it.

113
00:12:41,113 --> 00:12:46,083
And you mentally bring the energy up the spine, down to the stomach, up the spine.

114
00:12:46,124 --> 00:12:47,967
That's where the energy is supposed to move, isn't it?

115
00:12:48,509 --> 00:12:49,871
Tai Chi and all that.

116
00:12:49,851 --> 00:12:51,615
And you lift yourself up like that, you see.

117
00:12:51,634 --> 00:12:57,263
And as soon as you stop, then you may begin to feel the actual underlying disturbance which is causing this swaying.

118
00:12:57,524 --> 00:12:58,806
So that's what you have to deal with.

119
00:12:59,086 --> 00:12:59,706
That comes up.

120
00:12:59,746 --> 00:13:01,408
When it passes, no more swaying.

121
00:13:02,110 --> 00:13:07,357
Boom, boom.

122
00:13:07,379 --> 00:13:07,759
The breath.

123
00:13:07,918 --> 00:13:16,972
So sometimes now, you know, around about this time, people do start becoming much more calm, especially over the next two days, but even today.

124
00:13:17,947 --> 00:13:32,721
And there are moments during the meditation when there's this peacefulness comes, this great calm descends, the body's very still, the mind is not thinking, it's pretty empty, and the heart seems to be just calm, you see.

125
00:13:33,201 --> 00:13:35,283
And when you look, there's only the breath to watch.

126
00:13:35,784 --> 00:13:36,765
There's only the breath, you see.

127
00:13:38,047 --> 00:13:41,971
So at this point, a meditator might say, now what?

128
00:13:42,610 --> 00:13:46,554
See, because they're expecting some explosion or something, you know, something to happen.

129
00:13:46,972 --> 00:13:56,284
Well, the thing is that now there is this lovely moment to really plunge into the breath and to go towards the center of the breath, you see.

130
00:13:56,765 --> 00:14:03,875
And what we're doing is we are really beginning to focus in on specific area, right?

131
00:14:03,914 --> 00:14:16,591
The smaller the area, it's like when somebody studies for something like a higher degree or something, they always go to a really abstruse little bit.

132
00:14:17,028 --> 00:14:19,892
You know, like, why flies land on mushrooms.

133
00:14:20,633 --> 00:14:22,696
You know, and there's a whole thesis on that.

134
00:14:22,796 --> 00:14:31,587
And so, as we go into the middle of the breath, as we go into the middle of the breath, you see, we're really sharpening the focus.

135
00:14:31,668 --> 00:14:33,590
We're really sharpening the concentration.

136
00:14:34,010 --> 00:14:36,094
The intelligence is still there.

137
00:14:36,153 --> 00:14:37,855
There's still that question mark in the mind.

138
00:14:37,875 --> 00:14:40,480
There's still that sense of curiosity, of wanting to know.

139
00:14:41,360 --> 00:14:43,102
It's a relaxation, eh?

140
00:14:43,082 --> 00:14:48,207
If your forehead starts furrowing, you know, because you're doing this business, then that's wrong.

141
00:14:48,749 --> 00:14:50,211
Remember, this is a relaxation.

142
00:14:50,270 --> 00:14:52,173
This is driven by interest.

143
00:14:52,373 --> 00:14:55,096
Driven by interest, not a desire to concentrate.

144
00:14:55,735 --> 00:14:56,918
Driven by interest.

145
00:14:57,357 --> 00:15:03,965
And as you get closer and closer, you see, because of that focus, because of that focus, time is collapsing.

146
00:15:03,985 --> 00:15:04,085
See?

147
00:15:04,326 --> 00:15:06,148
I mean, how long is time?

148
00:15:06,227 --> 00:15:07,048
What does it feel like?

149
00:15:07,089 --> 00:15:10,471
It's a couple of seconds, isn't it, or something?

150
00:15:11,113 --> 00:15:11,232
Right?

151
00:15:13,086 --> 00:15:14,410
You know, right?

152
00:15:14,530 --> 00:15:15,573
It's about so long, isn't it?

153
00:15:16,075 --> 00:15:17,619
But in reality, it's not like that at all.

154
00:15:18,221 --> 00:15:19,163
It's moment to moment.

155
00:15:19,243 --> 00:15:22,832
It's minute, the way that things are arising and passing away.

156
00:15:23,514 --> 00:15:25,559
So, as we go into there...

157
00:15:25,674 --> 00:15:28,638
The whole of time is collapsing, you see, as we go in.

158
00:15:29,038 --> 00:15:36,447
And it's right here, you see, that we begin to see these things like I'll be talking about, this sense of transiency much clearer.

159
00:15:37,227 --> 00:15:49,822
And when we come out, when something does come up, and we have that sharpness of concentration, you see, which is now a quality of that looking, then, of course, we can see it more clearly.

160
00:15:50,503 --> 00:15:53,166
So don't waste those times, no matter how long they are.

161
00:15:53,186 --> 00:15:54,206
They're only a minute or so.

162
00:15:54,287 --> 00:15:55,327
Don't waste them, you see.

163
00:16:01,282 --> 00:16:07,208
So I think that covers this business of the things that came up for today.

164
00:16:09,410 --> 00:16:17,640
What I want to do is just, in a sense, complete the three characteristics and just go through them and see where it takes us.

165
00:16:18,741 --> 00:16:27,491
These other two are anicca, anatta, transience, impermanence, and this idea of not-self.

166
00:16:27,471 --> 00:16:36,701
Whereas dukkha, suffering, dissatisfaction, unsatisfactoriness, belongs to the realm of sentient beings, belongs to our realm specifically.

167
00:16:36,802 --> 00:16:38,003
It's us who suffer.

168
00:16:38,403 --> 00:16:38,823
It's us.

169
00:16:39,365 --> 00:16:45,672
But when it comes to transience and not-self, that's something which reaches out to the whole phenomenal world.

170
00:16:45,711 --> 00:16:48,715
Everything is in a state of arising and passing away.

171
00:16:48,774 --> 00:16:51,817
It is one eternal law that everything changes.

172
00:16:51,857 --> 00:16:53,799
It's one steady law in the universe.

173
00:16:54,120 --> 00:16:55,302
Everything is changing.

174
00:16:56,345 --> 00:16:59,831
And the other thing is that everything is not-self.

175
00:17:00,392 --> 00:17:12,952
So I want to start with this harder concept of not-self, just go through one or two ideas with you, and then to move to the easier one, which is this idea of transience, and let's see where it takes us.

176
00:17:16,847 --> 00:17:21,834
So the first thing about not-self is that that's not a philosophical statement.

177
00:17:21,874 --> 00:17:23,836
The Buddha's not saying there is no self.

178
00:17:24,376 --> 00:17:25,378
It's a teaching tool.

179
00:17:26,079 --> 00:17:34,269
It's a way of looking at what we're experiencing and beginning to see that there's no ghost within the machine.

180
00:17:35,230 --> 00:17:42,400
There's nothing sort of metaphysical about what we experience.

181
00:17:47,476 --> 00:17:51,622
Everything arises because it's in relationship with everything.

182
00:17:51,782 --> 00:17:55,568
Everything arises dependent on something.

183
00:17:55,989 --> 00:17:57,531
Dependent on something.

184
00:17:57,551 --> 00:18:00,556
So nothing has its own essential nature.

185
00:18:00,616 --> 00:18:02,539
Nothing has its own being.

186
00:18:04,241 --> 00:18:08,107
Now when I walk around, you know, I feel very individual.

187
00:18:08,268 --> 00:18:09,109
I think it's me.

188
00:18:09,611 --> 00:18:10,832
Me, I'm walking around.

189
00:18:10,853 --> 00:18:13,737
I have this feeling of being me.

190
00:18:14,746 --> 00:18:20,803
But when I look at this me, if I look at the body, I don't know where the me begins and the me ends.

191
00:18:20,863 --> 00:18:23,490
I mean, when does air become me?

192
00:18:24,913 --> 00:18:27,642
Does it become me when it's in the mouth or when it's in the blood?

193
00:18:28,921 --> 00:18:31,565
When does food I'm eating become me?

194
00:18:32,005 --> 00:18:34,489
There's a sort of boundary, isn't there?

195
00:18:36,270 --> 00:18:44,522
When I say these are my thoughts, how much thoughts are coming in which I'm taking up from radio and people I talk to and all that?

196
00:18:45,684 --> 00:18:49,410
What do I mean by my thoughts over this membrane?

197
00:18:51,465 --> 00:18:58,118
When I talk about emotions, sure, they're developed by me, but they're also to do with my relationship to people.

198
00:18:58,278 --> 00:18:59,221
They evoke things.

199
00:18:59,320 --> 00:19:05,854
So there's this sort of passage of communication between us, between nature, wherever I go.

200
00:19:05,874 --> 00:19:13,930
So this idea of me, sort of a sharp sort of wall around me, begins to sort of undo.

201
00:19:15,749 --> 00:19:28,890
Now this process of undoing, this process of deconstruction, which I've been pointing you to especially when you're doing the eating, is the main technique that the Buddha uses to get across his idea of not-self.

202
00:19:30,511 --> 00:19:36,361
Now, just to look at one of them, he talks about the five khandhas, the five aggregates.

203
00:19:36,821 --> 00:19:43,291
So he says, when you take a human being apart, what do you find?

204
00:19:43,406 --> 00:20:10,343
