Remember that the body is conditioned, isn't it?

241
00:22:50,313 --> 00:22:52,836
I mean, I can do certain things with it, but there's a blueprint there.

242
00:22:52,977 --> 00:22:55,000
It just follows the genome, you know?

243
00:22:55,500 --> 00:22:57,443
I can't do much about that.

244
00:22:57,785 --> 00:23:00,347
Perceptions are dependent on my brain and mind.

245
00:23:00,868 --> 00:23:01,971
I can't do much about that.

246
00:23:04,213 --> 00:23:05,876
Feelings are dependent.

247
00:23:05,856 --> 00:23:33,394
if somebody kicks me in the shin then it hurts and that's it I can't do anything about that it's just something arises but this whole business of emotions is something that I create through my will and that's what we're all beginning to understand by watching this process within us of these emotions arising and passing away and how we want to indulge them and all that so which feelings are we?

248
00:23:33,715 --> 00:23:34,497
I mean

249
00:23:35,134 --> 00:23:38,219
Are yesterday's feelings the same as today's feelings?

250
00:23:38,239 --> 00:23:40,201
Who am I now?

251
00:23:40,280 --> 00:23:43,345
Because yesterday I had these feelings, but now I've got different feelings.

252
00:23:43,365 --> 00:23:43,986
So who am I?

253
00:23:44,506 --> 00:23:46,669
Because the idea of a me is something static, isn't it?

254
00:23:46,709 --> 00:23:51,355
Something solid, something I can really point to and say, well, this is me.

255
00:23:51,976 --> 00:23:53,277
And the goalposts keep changing.

256
00:23:56,820 --> 00:23:58,983
And then finally there's consciousness.

257
00:23:59,664 --> 00:24:02,188
And consciousness is always dependent on the object.

258
00:24:03,838 --> 00:24:06,221
If there's no object to be conscious of, who are you?

259
00:24:06,682 --> 00:24:07,724
I mean, who are you in sleep?

260
00:24:13,393 --> 00:24:14,233
Where do you go in sleep?

261
00:24:16,576 --> 00:24:18,279
In the middle of your sleep, do you say, I'm still here?

262
00:24:19,961 --> 00:24:21,364
It's gone, isn't it?

263
00:24:21,384 --> 00:24:21,984
There's no me.

264
00:24:24,008 --> 00:24:26,811
It's not that there's not awareness there, but there's definitely not a sense of me.

265
00:24:31,940 --> 00:24:33,541
If, for instance...

266
00:24:33,943 --> 00:24:38,311
The doctor said to you, listen, you've got this very, very strange and terrible disease.

267
00:24:39,413 --> 00:24:41,397
If you fall asleep, you will die.

268
00:24:43,642 --> 00:24:44,383
Are you going to fall asleep?

269
00:24:46,666 --> 00:24:47,888
See?

270
00:24:47,909 --> 00:24:51,675
The reason why we fall asleep is because we presume I'm going to appear again in the morning.

271
00:24:52,817 --> 00:24:53,779
I wake up and there I am.

272
00:24:54,260 --> 00:24:54,821
Me again.

273
00:25:03,256 --> 00:25:16,209
So we have to really look at this and begin to experience things and realize that this concept of me being this body, me being this personality, me being this character, I can't sustain that, at least not at an intellectual level.

274
00:25:16,949 --> 00:25:17,910
I can't sustain it.

275
00:25:18,250 --> 00:25:19,991
So what the meditation does, it takes us in.

276
00:25:20,031 --> 00:25:23,895
And by seeing this distancing, that's why we distance.

277
00:25:23,915 --> 00:25:24,916
That's the first position.

278
00:25:25,278 --> 00:25:28,421
By distancing, we're looking at an object.

279
00:25:28,661 --> 00:25:30,883
If it's an object, it can't be the subject.

280
00:25:31,791 --> 00:25:34,516
I can't be what I'm looking at.

281
00:25:36,278 --> 00:25:40,482
Because there's a distance there, isn't there?

282
00:25:40,502 --> 00:25:48,894
So when we make that distance very obvious to ourselves, in ourselves, we're creating that objectivity, that not-self.

283
00:25:48,913 --> 00:25:49,835
And that's what the Buddha says.

284
00:25:49,875 --> 00:25:57,545
When you look in and you feel something, just say, not me, not mine, not a self.

285
00:25:57,565 --> 00:25:58,946
The body's not a self.

286
00:25:59,939 --> 00:26:02,382
It's not me and it's not mine and it's not a self.

287
00:26:04,163 --> 00:26:07,268
Emotions, they're not me, they're not mine and they're not a self.

288
00:26:08,849 --> 00:26:12,734
Feelings in the body are not me, they're not mine and they're not a self.

289
00:26:14,478 --> 00:26:20,125
The consciousness that arises knowing things is not me, not mine, not a self.

290
00:26:23,547 --> 00:26:31,720
So these little reflections, you see, they slowly sort of burst through the bubble, they burst through the hard sort of idea of me.

291
00:26:33,643 --> 00:26:37,328
And of course it's frightening, isn't it?

292
00:26:38,451 --> 00:26:45,701
Because as we'll do towards the end, the point of me, where me really comes to an end, the point of death, is very frightening for us.

293
00:26:46,343 --> 00:26:47,664
Who am I when I die?

294
00:26:54,242 --> 00:27:07,019
So that's part of the idea that the Buddha uses to deconstruct, you see, the idea of deconstructing something, to see that there's no self, there's no me, no I, no self.

295
00:27:07,039 --> 00:27:08,701
The other thing he points to is control.

296
00:27:09,823 --> 00:27:17,673
See, this whole idea of free will, you know, it's badgered Western philosophy ever since, free will.

297
00:27:18,213 --> 00:27:22,900
So I walk into a supermarket, and there's something like a hundred biscuits there.

298
00:27:22,946 --> 00:27:24,189
And I think, fantastic.

299
00:27:25,810 --> 00:27:29,675
I have free will to choose any biscuit I want.

300
00:27:30,257 --> 00:27:32,640
And I go along the shelf and I come across Crunch It.

301
00:27:33,760 --> 00:27:36,984
And I pick it up and it says, Crunch It really puts you in a good mood.

302
00:27:37,006 --> 00:27:39,528
And I think, Crunch It?

303
00:27:39,909 --> 00:27:40,509
Crunch It?

304
00:27:40,549 --> 00:27:41,490
I've never heard of that.

305
00:27:41,510 --> 00:27:42,673
I'll put it back.

306
00:27:42,692 --> 00:27:45,737
Then you walk back and you see, McVitie's chocolate biscuits.

307
00:27:45,757 --> 00:27:46,919
Oh, that's what I want.

308
00:27:47,199 --> 00:27:48,601
Chocolate biscuits.

309
00:27:48,621 --> 00:27:51,064
I have exercised my free will.

310
00:27:52,951 --> 00:27:53,993
Totally conditioned, isn't it?

311
00:27:56,179 --> 00:27:57,682
I have free speech.

312
00:27:57,943 --> 00:28:00,451
I will say exactly what I want.

313
00:28:05,624 --> 00:28:06,125
Anytime.

314
00:28:06,506 --> 00:28:08,731
I can say exactly what I want anytime.

315
00:28:12,188 --> 00:28:12,969
It's conditioned, isn't it?

316
00:28:12,989 --> 00:28:15,192
I only say something if somebody asks me to say something.

317
00:28:15,833 --> 00:28:17,375
If somebody gives me an opinion on something.

318
00:28:17,835 --> 00:28:22,942
Everything I say is dependent on my history, my ideas, my connections.

319
00:28:27,406 --> 00:28:28,989
I have free will.

320
00:28:29,309 --> 00:28:30,070
Perfectly free will.

321
00:28:30,090 --> 00:28:31,853
I can vote for whomever I want.

322
00:28:33,796 --> 00:28:36,358
I don't never vote for liberals.

323
00:28:36,378 --> 00:28:37,059
Conservatives?

324
00:28:37,079 --> 00:28:38,922
No, I'm fed up with black.

325
00:28:39,559 --> 00:28:40,821
I'm not going to vote.

326
00:28:40,842 --> 00:28:42,243
I have exercised my free will.

327
00:28:44,067 --> 00:28:45,288
Driven by prejudice.

328
00:28:45,949 --> 00:28:47,612
Driven by hatred and greed.

329
00:28:48,633 --> 00:28:50,115
But I've exercised my free will.

330
00:28:51,798 --> 00:28:52,038
See?

331
00:28:52,479 --> 00:29:02,614
So first of all, we have to get rid of that pathetic idea that somehow the will is some sort of floating entity that can choose whatever it wants to do my own thing in my own time and in my own way.

332
00:29:03,255 --> 00:29:03,394
Right?

333
00:29:03,414 --> 00:29:05,397
So we can get rid of that completely.

334
00:29:05,498 --> 00:29:05,617
Right?

335
00:29:06,796 --> 00:29:11,337
And then when we come down, we realize that in fact, we obviously have choices.

336
00:29:11,892 --> 00:29:13,575
And what we choose is conditioned.

337
00:29:14,316 --> 00:29:34,768
So now, if we want to get to some freedom not to do, but freedom from, freedom from conditioning, we need to know what are the conditionings that make me make certain choices, and do these choices lead to my personal comfort, my happiness, to my well-being?

338
00:29:35,048 --> 00:29:37,932
Does it lead to the well-being, comfort, and happiness of others?

339
00:29:38,503 --> 00:29:54,320
Now, if I can see the conditioning, and if I can see the choice, and if I can see the result of the choice, and I can then step back and reflect, is this skillful or not, you see, then I have some sort of choice to say no.

340
00:29:55,342 --> 00:30:01,147
But that no is coming from another conditioning which is arising out of the wisdom factor.

341
00:30:01,607 --> 00:30:05,231
Now, I'm not going to do anything which leads me to unhappiness.

342
00:30:05,392 --> 00:30:08,055
I'm not going to do anything which leads others to unhappiness.

343
00:30:09,672 --> 00:30:34,953
So everything is conditioned and yet we have this through the wisdom, through wisdom, the slow movement, the transformation of all our habits over to the other place from wicked to wonderful just by exercising this reflection driven by the idea of goodness, beauty, love and all that sort of stuff.

344
00:30:38,038 --> 00:30:41,723
Even when we do that and we've come to know it, there's no free will about it.

345
00:30:42,305 --> 00:30:43,385
There's nothing free about it.

346
00:30:43,707 --> 00:30:44,508
You're compelled.

347
00:30:45,148 --> 00:30:50,336
As soon as you realize that something's doing you harm, you don't do it anymore.

348
00:30:50,355 --> 00:30:52,838
As soon as you realize something's doing you good, then you start doing that.

349
00:30:54,862 --> 00:30:58,606
So there's something within us which is dry, it's driven.

350
00:30:58,767 --> 00:30:59,508
It is driven.

351
00:30:59,548 --> 00:31:01,430
It's not within the bounds of our ego.

352
00:31:01,450 --> 00:31:05,615
It's not within the bounds of our choice, which is being driven to the Enlightenment.

353
00:31:07,739 --> 00:31:13,108
The whole world is so manufactured to drive us, herd us, towards the enlightenment.

354
00:31:13,128 --> 00:31:13,970
We don't have a choice.

355
00:31:15,251 --> 00:31:18,057
Even when you're in hell, it doesn't last that long.

356
00:31:19,240 --> 00:31:21,723
And then when you come out, you realize, God, I've been in hell.

357
00:31:23,666 --> 00:31:24,548
I don't want to go there again.

358
00:31:24,568 --> 00:31:26,231
I'm not going down that road again.

359
00:31:26,291 --> 00:31:27,334
See?

360
00:31:29,051 --> 00:31:33,738
So the whole process is one of learning because of this intelligence.

361
00:31:33,798 --> 00:31:36,561
It's this intelligence that wants to get out of suffering.

362
00:31:36,582 --> 00:31:38,904
It's this intelligence that wants to get out of dissatisfaction.

363
00:31:42,130 --> 00:31:44,814
And yet there is something which is unconditioned.

364
00:31:45,875 --> 00:31:50,300
So we chant in the morning, this little chant from the Buddha, aneka jati sansaram.

365
00:31:51,377 --> 00:31:59,250
And he says, I've been through loads of rebirths, loads and loads, and I've constantly been pulled by the nose, by this self, by this ego.

366
00:31:59,770 --> 00:32:01,031
But now, he says, I've seen you.

367
00:32:01,512 --> 00:32:07,182
I've broken your ridge pole, I've pulled down your house, and you're definitely not going to build another ego and self for me.

368
00:32:08,282 --> 00:32:11,868
And he says, I have destroyed all my impurities, everything is gone, he says.

369
00:32:11,888 --> 00:32:15,394
And I have achieved the unconditioned consciousness.

370
00:32:17,752 --> 00:32:22,180
That unconditioned consciousness of the Buddha still, while he's here, still has to live in the world.

371
00:32:23,762 --> 00:32:25,265
So his body tells him he's hungry.

372
00:32:25,945 --> 00:32:27,930
So he goes out and gets some food and he eats food.

373
00:32:28,770 --> 00:32:30,974
And when somebody comes to him and says, now what's all this stuff about?

374
00:32:31,536 --> 00:32:32,317
He has to respond.

375
00:32:33,960 --> 00:32:36,723
He's using the language of the time, which is totally conditioned.

376
00:32:39,016 --> 00:33:06,828
so that's why he says that the feeling of moving towards the enlightenment is a freedom from not a freedom to do something but a freedom from a freedom from compulsion so when we talk about control that's coming from ego that's coming from ego trying to control things power and all that

377
00:33:10,791 --> 00:33:15,940
When we understand rightly, then we understand that we're in relationship.

378
00:33:15,960 --> 00:33:17,942
And that it's always a contract.

379
00:33:18,103 --> 00:33:19,384
We're always moving around.

380
00:33:20,907 --> 00:33:24,093
You decide that you're going to go for a picnic and the weather's pouring.

381
00:33:24,973 --> 00:33:25,535
That's okay.

382
00:33:26,056 --> 00:33:28,058
You take an umbrella.

383
00:33:28,078 --> 00:33:28,799
You work with it.

384
00:33:33,640 --> 00:33:42,813
So now I want to get onto Anicca, which is, in a sense, a more easy concept, because we can all see everything's arising and passing away.

385
00:33:43,394 --> 00:33:45,416
But how much do we see it?

386
00:33:45,798 --> 00:33:48,280
We see it out there, and we want it, we love it.

387
00:33:48,902 --> 00:33:50,463
Who wouldn't want winter and summer?

388
00:33:50,984 --> 00:33:51,826
They're a lovely balance.

389
00:33:51,865 --> 00:33:53,288
You don't get that in the East, for instance.

390
00:33:53,307 --> 00:33:54,109
It's always the same.

391
00:33:57,153 --> 00:33:59,277
But it's when change hits us...

392
00:34:00,589 --> 00:34:01,431
Old age.

393
00:34:02,492 --> 00:34:02,792
Death.

394
00:34:03,213 --> 00:34:03,433
See?

395
00:34:03,653 --> 00:34:04,736
They're changing upwards.

396
00:34:07,318 --> 00:34:08,661
That's when we don't want to look at it.

397
00:34:09,242 --> 00:34:16,132
That's when we avert our eyes and we don't really recognize that this change is something happening within us, internal.

398
00:34:19,956 --> 00:34:27,907
And because we don't recognize that and we stay with moments, we stay with it, we create this idea of continuity which feeds into the idea of self.

399
00:34:27,989 --> 00:34:29,010
It's always me.

400
00:34:30,273 --> 00:34:33,416
But just look at the body you were born with.

401
00:34:34,918 --> 00:34:36,239
That little screaming hulk.

402
00:34:38,242 --> 00:34:39,242
How much of it is left now?

403
00:34:39,742 --> 00:34:41,045
It doesn't exist anymore, does it?

404
00:34:41,644 --> 00:34:42,646
That baby is dead.

405
00:34:44,007 --> 00:34:44,969
That body is dead.

406
00:34:46,269 --> 00:34:48,733
It died within seven years, according to our science.

407
00:34:49,373 --> 00:34:52,097
Every cell, every atom in that body was replaced.

408
00:34:52,916 --> 00:34:58,103
That whole body has very slowly, unwittingly just dissipated, just disappeared, disappeared.

409
00:35:00,427 --> 00:35:05,414
When you look in the mirror next time, you can say to that face, you weren't here seven years ago.

410
00:35:10,119 --> 00:35:11,722
That's what transiency is.

411
00:35:12,081 --> 00:35:12,802
Things are changing.

412
00:35:12,822 --> 00:35:22,094
And yet, because we have this idea, because I can show you through photographs that it was me, that little screaming hulk that doesn't look anything like me now, was me.

413
00:35:23,295 --> 00:35:24,416
Was me.

414
00:35:26,259 --> 00:35:27,059
Crazy, eh?

415
00:35:29,655 --> 00:35:31,018
How can you be a was-me?

416
00:35:32,260 --> 00:35:33,222
You've got to be me now.

417
00:35:33,262 --> 00:35:34,123
You can't be me then.

418
00:35:35,646 --> 00:35:37,570
But I launch myself into the future.

419
00:35:38,012 --> 00:35:40,456
So I'm going to appear without any doubt tomorrow.

420
00:35:41,677 --> 00:35:43,221
I know exactly what I'm doing tomorrow.

421
00:35:44,063 --> 00:35:45,686
I'm coming here to meditate in the morning.

422
00:35:45,806 --> 00:35:46,887
That's me.

423
00:35:49,989 --> 00:35:53,675
So this idea of transiency also has to be sort of undone.

424
00:35:53,755 --> 00:35:59,663
And it's undone by seeing, just seeing that process, just seeing it, by being aware of it.

425
00:36:00,284 --> 00:36:06,992
And when we see it inwardly and it brings up fear, so that's what we've got to look at because this fear is coming from the ego.

426
00:36:07,012 --> 00:36:09,436
Fear is the last barrier of the self.

427
00:36:09,856 --> 00:36:11,239
That's how it protects itself.

428
00:36:12,603 --> 00:36:15,706
There's no worse emotion than fear.

429
00:36:16,168 --> 00:36:21,375
You may think there is, but fear is the last thing that the self has to protect itself.

430
00:36:24,840 --> 00:36:30,967
So when fear comes up, you see, that's really something to really move towards.

431
00:36:30,987 --> 00:36:34,032
And what you find, of course, is where there's fear, there's the fear of fear.

432
00:36:34,552 --> 00:36:35,434
And you bounce off it.

433
00:36:36,215 --> 00:36:38,938
And when you're afraid of fear, you get into panic.

434
00:36:39,139 --> 00:36:39,960
That's what panic is.

435
00:36:40,320 --> 00:36:40,902
And you lose it.

436
00:36:40,922 --> 00:36:41,782
You just run away.

437
00:36:42,960 --> 00:36:49,666
So when fear of fear comes up, you look at the fear, you stay with that, you try and stay steady between the two, as it were, you know?

438
00:36:50,228 --> 00:36:51,708
Very difficult, but you stay steady.

439
00:36:51,949 --> 00:36:56,072
And slowly you keep averting your attention to the fear, the original fear.

440
00:36:56,452 --> 00:36:59,175
And as you get close to it, you begin to lose your fear of it.

441
00:37:00,317 --> 00:37:01,217
Just because of feeling.

442
00:37:01,277 --> 00:37:05,121
It's just another state, it's just another mental state, another emotion, another feeling.

443
00:37:05,722 --> 00:37:06,422
It's all it is.

444
00:37:06,583 --> 00:37:08,083
Not me, not mine, not self.

445
00:37:09,806 --> 00:37:12,427
And when we finally lose fear of fear...

446
00:37:13,117 --> 00:37:14,117
What the hell's going to frighten us?

447
00:37:18,121 --> 00:37:21,945
See, so the problem isn't the object, the problem isn't the wild beast attacking you.

448
00:37:23,786 --> 00:37:24,728
The problem is the fear.

449
00:37:25,467 --> 00:37:31,393
As soon as you let go of fear, as soon as you can feel fear and not become afraid by fear, then nothing will frighten you.

450
00:37:32,375 --> 00:37:36,539
And that's a sign to the person that they've undone this idea of ego, of self.

451
00:37:37,559 --> 00:37:40,001
The Buddha's often referred to as the fearless one.

452
00:37:40,184 --> 00:37:41,065
There is no fear.

453
00:37:41,545 --> 00:37:43,686
What is an enlightened person going to be afraid of?

454
00:37:48,331 --> 00:37:49,293
Who can hurt you anyway?

455
00:37:49,333 --> 00:37:50,873
What can people do to you?

456
00:37:51,074 --> 00:37:52,675
What can the world do to you?

457
00:37:52,695 --> 00:37:53,757
They can only do to your body.

458
00:37:55,498 --> 00:37:56,719
They can't hurt you emotionally.

459
00:37:57,501 --> 00:37:59,422
Nobody can cause you psychological pain.

460
00:38:02,304 --> 00:38:06,028
Even when somebody comes to me and says, you're a very stupid, bald-headed monk.

461
00:38:09,132 --> 00:38:09,211
See?

462
00:38:09,360 --> 00:38:10,262
I swear, isn't it?

463
00:38:10,282 --> 00:38:10,842
It stopped here.

464
00:38:11,623 --> 00:38:12,003
That's all.

465
00:38:12,063 --> 00:38:12,443
It stopped here.

466
00:38:13,324 --> 00:38:13,925
But it's me, isn't it?

467
00:38:13,945 --> 00:38:14,445
I take it in.

468
00:38:14,766 --> 00:38:24,577
Of course I forgive you.

469
00:38:24,597 --> 00:38:25,157
But it's me, isn't it?

470
00:38:25,197 --> 00:38:28,760
I've created this hatred, this aversion, because I've heard these words.

471
00:38:29,262 --> 00:38:31,523
And then I create a relationship with this person.

472
00:38:33,326 --> 00:38:34,407
Tell them what I think of them.

473
00:38:36,023 --> 00:38:38,467
So nobody can cause us psychological pain.

474
00:38:38,507 --> 00:38:41,570
So the worst the world can do to us is cause us physical pain.

475
00:38:42,733 --> 00:38:53,329
But if we're not the body, if it's not me, not mine, you've sat there now in meditation and you've been able to get some distance between that physical pain and you can see that there's an equanimity with it, you can stay with it.

476
00:38:54,510 --> 00:39:01,119
If there's a total detachment from it, if there's no connection whatsoever with pain, how can it hurt?

477
00:39:11,326 --> 00:39:15,293
So I want now to just draw us to a sort of conclusion.

478
00:39:15,333 --> 00:39:20,563
And I want us to draw us to an exercise which I'll be doing at the beginning of every last session.

479
00:39:20,905 --> 00:39:24,771
And it's just to bring to mind, you see, sickness, old age and death.

480
00:39:26,135 --> 00:39:28,900
These are the three things that drew the Buddha to his enlightenment.

481
00:39:29,061 --> 00:39:33,789
When he saw a sick person, you know, a very old person and a dead and a corpse.

482
00:39:35,255 --> 00:39:36,717
Each time he said, what is this?

483
00:39:36,757 --> 00:39:39,043
He'd been sheltered from this sort of stuff.

484
00:39:39,063 --> 00:39:40,646
And each time they said, well, he's a human being.

485
00:39:40,686 --> 00:39:42,630
And then the big question, does this happen to me?

486
00:39:42,690 --> 00:39:44,375
And that shook him.

487
00:39:44,394 --> 00:39:46,699
That sent him into a sort of tizzy.

488
00:39:47,181 --> 00:39:48,724
He had a nervous breakdown and ran off.

489
00:39:49,887 --> 00:39:50,708
So I'm going to be a monk.

490
00:39:51,650 --> 00:39:55,018
So now you know why people have got monks.

491
00:39:57,579 --> 00:40:01,367
So these meditations are to undo.

492
00:40:02,148 --> 00:40:09,103
He says when we meditate on the fact that this body can become sick, we undermine this intoxication we have with health, this worry.

493
00:40:10,105 --> 00:40:16,978
These household gyms and stuff like that worry about vitamins and diets and all that sort of stuff.

494
00:40:16,998 --> 00:40:19,503
It's all this obsession with health.

495
00:40:20,918 --> 00:40:22,019
He undoes the obsession.

496
00:40:22,099 --> 00:40:23,543
It doesn't mean you don't care for yourself.

497
00:40:23,922 --> 00:40:25,766
It's just undoing the obsession with health.

498
00:40:26,507 --> 00:40:34,563
He says when we contemplate old age, it gets rid of our obsession with youth, with wanting to be young, to be forever flowering.

499
00:40:36,525 --> 00:40:37,387
Can't decay.

500
00:40:39,090 --> 00:40:39,190
Ugly.

501
00:40:39,692 --> 00:40:39,871
Terrible.

502
00:40:41,000 --> 00:41:06,670
and when we contemplate death we undermine this very intoxication this enchantment this utter dependency we have on life itself so we're undermining that and what does that bring it brings a freedom it brings a freedom from obsession with health a freedom from having to look beautiful and young a freedom from having to live having to exist

503
00:41:09,164 --> 00:41:10,545
That compulsiveness.

504
00:41:10,686 --> 00:41:12,268
It's always getting rid of compulsiveness.

505
00:41:14,090 --> 00:41:26,686
And just to put us in the mood, I'd like to read this little poem from my favourite author, Samuel Beckett, whose work is a total meditation on last moments.

506
00:41:28,929 --> 00:41:30,371
Consciousness.

507
00:41:30,391 --> 00:41:30,990
It's up to you.

508
00:41:31,172 --> 00:41:34,715
Sometimes I close my eyes when I listen to poetry and sort of look at it.

509
00:41:41,614 --> 00:42:09,411
Just think if all this, one day, all this, one fine day, just think if one day, one fine day, all this stopped.

510
00:42:14,385 --> 00:42:24,126
Just think.

511
00:42:24,146 --> 00:42:26,610
I hope my words have been of some use to you.

512
00:42:26,650 --> 00:42:30,858
May you be enlightened even within these seven days.

